76561198290161320,Recommended,237870,31784977,Posted: 16 May,all,Arskov,"I've always loved creating things and seeing those things put to use in a game. It's what drew me to modding, what makes Space Engineers one of my favorite games of all time, and why I love survival games. Now with that said, Planet Explorers has set the bar for me. Any survival game will let you make things. Minecraft will let you make houses and castles and god knows what else. Space Engineers will let you make starships and stations and a whole pile of other things. But never have I seen a game that lets you design things as basic as your weapons and armor. And it's not just allowed, it's encouraged! Sure the voxel system takes a little getting used to, but once you figure it out the possibilities are literally endless. Got a favorite gun from another game or a movie? Bam. Make it. Like someone's clothes in a show? Bam. Make it. Want to drive around in the Oscar-Meyer Wienermobile? Bam. Make it.Gameplay-wise PE is a little rough. Like any open-world sandbox game there are issues. For some games those issues can be a deal-breaker, but PE? In this case, the pros FAR outweigh the cons. Sure the graphics can be a bit janky at times and I can't help but wonder what the dev team's primary language is ('cause it sure as hell wasn't English), but the game itself is solid. The crafting system is steamlined, the gathering isn't nearly as sadisticly grindy as most survival games, and the worlds are interesting to explore and colonize. I can easily lose myself for hours on end with this game, which is nice given that I recently started working for a different company and am now working the graveyard. With nothing to do but wait for calls to come in, this game makes the time in between fly by.All in all I highly recommend this game to anyone who enjoys surivival games or is looking to try one for the first time... and I'm always excited to see what both the community and the dev team have in store for us.P.S.: Be careful when setting up a custom map. It's quite easy to end up with something that looks like a 20-square-kilometer setpiece for Waterworld. @.@"
,Recommended,237870,26492946,"Posted: 8 November, 2016",all,rockyjvec,"I've been playing this game on and off since the very beginning of the Early Access.  It's one of, if not my favorite game in the Sandbox/Open World/Survival genre.  You should consider this as an early access review since I haven't yet played the release version of the game.What sets this game apart from other games like it is that it has an epic story and feel, and the story mode can be played coop.  It's a ""go at your own pace"" story where you do quests and/or side quests which usually reward you with gear/recipes. However, you can also skip all the quests and just purchase most of the gear/recipes at the npc shops if you prefer to do it that way.The scenery is awesome and many locations feel epic.  This is because in story mode the terrain was hand crafted and not randomly generated like other games.  There are plains, deserts, huge forests with giant trees, etc. each with different creatures.  The creatures and vegetation are some of the most unique and alien I have seen in any game.  I believe in the adventure game mode the terrain is randomly generated but I haven't played that mode much yet.The crafting system is very unique and you can build custom weapons, vehicles, boats, helicopters, etc. and the materials you use matter.  NPC ""shops"" exist where you can buy most of the recipes or if you are patient you can do quests which usually reward you with recipes and/or items.Once you have discovered a point of interest in the game, you can spend the game's currency (meat) to fast travel between any point of interest, It has a unique mining system where you can scan for ore deposits, and you can put comments on the map, so you can get back to the deposits later. The voxel terrain is destructable, and contains underground caverns to explore.  You mine for ores, cut down trees, hunt beasts, etc. to get materials for crafting.I personally really like the sound track.I can't think of much not to like about this game. I guess bugs were probably the greatest deterrent a while back.  Multiplayer had some syncing issues when I last played it a few months before the release but most of the bugs were tolerable at that time.  I'm guessing they have fixed most of them for full release and I can't wait to do a full play through again now that it is out of early access.The game also has several other game modes.  I haven't tried them so I won't comment on them.  The coop story mode is almost everything I have always wanted in an Open Sorld/Sandbox game.I highly recommend this game."
