76561198022247983,Not Recommended,237870,26642725,"Posted: 17 November, 2016",all,Mogg,"This review is based on multiplayer story mode via LAN.Bought an played on 17 Nov.UPDATED 26 NOVI wont explain to you all what the game is about since you most likely have already watched a few videos and read the game's description. If not, take the intiative to do so before reading on.Here I will provide a list of findings from myself and my gaming partner playing through story mode on ""LAN"" setting.My considered PROs.--------------------------------1) Single player game mode doesn't require an internet connection.2) Creativity. This needs further clarification. You can design your own gear, and vehicles with a combination of premade 3d parts and voxels (cubes), which includes a somewhat rough ability to colour them as well. Once designing is complete, as long as you have the required materials in your inventory you are able to bring this design into the world as a fully usable/interactable object, as well as it will upload this creation to Steam's workshop.If you aren't the creative sort, you have the ability to download other people's uplaoded creations.3) The world itself is huge to try and fit as many different land types as possible onto a single island.4) As long you wield gear bought from NPCs or crafted from your replicator, combat doesn't last long against almost all opponents you face.My considered UNSURE OFs.--------------------------------------------1) Quests mostly consist of gathering specific items, talking to particular people, moving to a specific location on the map and killing specific critters and buildings. There are singular instances of getting the player to make use of user created content, introductory tool for players to make their own content.2) Few quests require the construction of objects you do not have access to unless you find other specific NPCs to do their quests as well. When you do gain the object scripts (recipies or crafting papers you learn how to build stuff from) through quests they are useless since you will automatically already know how to produce them. Inventory clutter.3) There is no inventory limit of any sort. While not a bad thing in of itself (and certainly not an issue unless you are looking for some kind of realism XD), it is rather amusing to be able to just pull a colossal boat / car / tank / flying machine / buidling out of your pocket and when you are finished using it, able to pick it up and put it back into your pocket. If there is a limit, I have yet to reach it.4) There is no levelling at all here to be done. A character's strengths and weaknesses are directly tied to the gear you wear and wield.5) illnesses exist but are an incredibley rare occurance since they require very specific things to make them happen. A rather pointless addition.My considered CONs.--------------------------------1) LAN requires players to have internet access. ( wtf )2) Quitting a LAN game, PE_Server.exe will continue to run the background which counts as the game still running. Need to manually close it through the windows task manager.3) Syncronization. Cause delays in actions, and animations to not play when they should.4) in LAN game, characters and NPCs ignoring player placed blocks. This will lead to NPCs impossible to interact with should they be several layers under placed flooring. NPCs will also plant crops under player placed blocks should there be any fertilized soil under them.5) Some items created are largely useless. Created swords wont ever be as effective (roughly 1/3 as effective in fact) as those you can buy from NPCs or build from their scripts, uless you are planning on having over-the-top huge anime swords). Vehicles are largely useless except the helicopter, and even then you only need to use it to get to a destination once as fast travel exists.6) To edit any of your custom creations you will need to build an entire new one. You can get back all the materials for your original custom creation by recyling/deconstructing it however, it will need to have 100% durabilty to refund all of its materials used. You can't just add to your custom object without rebuilding the entire thing. I personally understand the reasoning for this choice however it creates the next point below.7) Any kind of recreation of custom item will be put into steam's workshop again. No, this doesn't replace what you've already put onto the workshop.8) Steam workshop clutter from everybody having created something. You'll see a host of copies of the same named thing and no idea how any of them a re different, if at all.9) The controls for creating custom things is not explained in detail anywhere easily.10) Some of the game's missions are very vague. Good thing there are people who will answer how to complete them. There shouldn't be a requirement to look up an outside source to understand what a quest requires a player to do.11) Talking with an NPC does not stop them from wandering off. This doesn't affect conversations, as they can still be finished. Shops, however, close once the NPC moves a certain distance away from the player.The experience is ok as a casual thing. Still there's a lot of room for improvement and from my opinion should still be in early access given the large number of issues present.I paid for this at full price. Developers these days a pretty eager to just shove their product out there regardless how complete and functional it may be. I wouldn't recommend this as it is right now, not until it gets some major fixes. Also it would be wise to change the ""LAN"" aspect since this isn't LAN at all.I'll try to keep this updated with the help of anyone who kindly informs me of my mistakes or game updates."
76561198046908290,Not Recommended,237870,17811129,"Posted: 31 August, 2015",all,n_games55555,"So my only main concern with this game right now is why did they change how the clustering works with resources you gather. It seems to me that in some patch (while I wasn't playing for idk how long), they decided that resources you gather shouldn't be completely clustered together and should have alot of trash resources, like dirt and stone, in the way. That sense of a realistic touch.. is a bit too much for me. It already took a bit of time and effort to find and gather them. It seems to me as if its take up a rediculous amount more time to gather resources now, making the game undesireable when I feel like I'm spending all day trying to get materials, instead of building the many awesome buildings / vehicles / miscellaneous objects.Take a look at my hours spent in game and you'll know I'm not fibbing. I seriously had a lot of fun up until now. Now it is a serious grind session. I'll not be playing a game if the work to fun ratio is heavily disproportionate. That being said, I currently will not recommend this game. I will check back in months coming to see progress and hopefully change my mind.My suggestion to fix the problem would be to either make resource gathering the way it was (heavily clustered no trash in the way), or give us better gathering tools to mine through resources at a faster (or MUCH faster) rate.You guys would also get extra bonus credit from me if you got rid of the 3ish second 'waiting to stop gathering resources so my character can do something ANYTHING again' wait time. Double bonus credit if you allow me to move while mining."
76561198068131974,Recommended,237870,34429635,Posted: 22 August,all,Nobody Important,"This game made me sad and mad about it but overall i still have to recommend it. Here's why:The premise of the game, a voxel based, actually nice looking, survival and building adventure, with character customization, in a sci-fi setting, with a story, is basically the sum total of anything i'd ever want from a game. In other words, at least for me, *the perfect game*. Just building anything you want and moving around in it, building sprawling and nice bases, altering your environment to suit your liking, and to get new materials, all while there is an underlying story. Awesomeness.However, the perfection fails to materialise if you look at the small details.You cannot build with glass, which in my opinion is one of the worst things about the game. It makes no sense and couldn't have been that hard to implement either. At least give us craftable windows or something! How is one supposed to build a sci fi looking base without those?Then there's the second biggest gripe, that the building blocks used to create items are very strictly separated into categories. Why? Why shouldn't i be able to build a hovercraft with a bed in it? This would be very simple to fix and yet somehow no one thought of it.Speaking of building limitations, the limitations for the base are ridiculous. You have a brilliantly smooth looking voxel terrain engine, and you cannot build underground bases. You have tons of water and watercraft and ""realistic"" physics for going underwater, and you cannot build underwater bases. Of course this can be modified retroactively by covering the base later, but the limitations don't end there. You cannot have more than one processing plant and you cannot have more than 5 people assigned to it. Similar things are found throughout. There is only one colony bed type and it's group beds, so if you wanted to create individual rooms for colonists, tough luck. Again could be fixed in 2 minutes. In general why can't one just build moving or flying bases. Why isn't there a crafting recipe for just all the objects in the world? Why can't you have two bases? Why can't you individualize the base parts?The engine is one where you could theoretically recreate the frikkin ship you came in, and yet, somehow it was chosen to limit it.There are some smaller gripes, like the in-world building tasks, where you only have to do two during the whole game.Or that the voice acting isn't perfect, and some minor characters lack voices, and that talking in a moving vehicle causes problems. Along with the starting cutscene just being badly edited.The text sometimes feels wrong too.The armor helmets could potentially be betterThen there's the fact that *spoiler alert* some characters die and it doesn't quite feel heavy enough.A lot of these things are easily fixed, and could even be fixed by modders, and as the developers are still very much active on it there is hope that some will get fixed.The actual reason why i still recommend this game is comparatively simple though:It is fun!It is loads and loads and loads of fun.There are some people complaining about a bit too much grind or fetching, but overall the game is still fun to play even through those times.The scenery is beautiful and almost realistic, the flora and fauna are awe inspiring, and you get lots of opportunity for creativity, while being ensnared by a captivating and complex story.I cannot emphasize enough how nice the game feels. The music is pleasant and fitting, the transportation methods are fun to use and customize, the exploration is adorable, the progressive base building and micromanagement give you the feeling of actually managing something with weight and complexity.Plus there is the multiplayer.Generally the game looks very much like an unpolished gemstone.But even unpolished gems are still very much rare in their beauty and absolutely worthwhile."
76561198025394635,Recommended,237870,13497456,"Posted: 21 December, 2014",all,Cpt.Selva[Hk] - Off for Concurso,"This game is still on early but it's extraordinary.It's remembers me a lot of Project Entropia with a bit of Space Engineers and Minecraft.Really open, creative, enjoyable and fun.Even on early it can give you lots of fun since theres lot of things to discover and do.This game is really recommended for those who like adventures with a lot of crafting and building.Overall 8/10 ( really good for an early acess imao)"
,Recommended,237870,26508925,"Posted: 9 November, 2016",all,Devilfish,"I've now played about 60 hours in story mode, most of it on the final build. In that time I've experienced one crash to desktop and three slowdowns so bad I had to quit and restart, but overall I've had a very good technical experience on max settings. The game looks great and the gameplay is fun and varied. Some of the locations are absolutely gorgeous and the design on some of the creatures is very impressive. Creation is a blast, but if you don't enjoy the process (understandable, as it does get rather fiddly) you can just as easily download ISOs or use ingame templates and items. Item creation is not a must to finish story mode, it's just another fun thing to do. The soundtrack is amazing. I'm probably buying the OST too, and that's something I've only ever done for one other game.Combat is pretty basic. Once you get decent weapons, there's not much of a threat. (Tip: almost everything can be circle-strafed to death.) There's enough of a challenge to keep it engaging, but it's not very complex. You've got your attack and defense, ranged or melee, and that's pretty much it. I'd call it elegant rather than simplistic, but YMMV.There's some negatives. The voice acting ranges from bad to atrocious, some plot twists are really awkwardly handled and most of the NPCs spend their days stuck in walls and falling through terrain. This is never gamebreaking, at least not in my case. My character does a lot of clipping through walls and getting stuck on the terrain, but never to the point where I have to reload. Neither me or an NPC have ever gotten irrevocably stuck, but it is annoying. Your own Minecraft-style buildings and vehicles can look jarringly blocky and out of place in the beautiful smooth landscape if you're not willing to spend many, many hours lovingly crafting them. Add it all up and you end up with a game that's very engaging, but not very immersive.Still, the good outweighs the bad by a very large margin, and patches are still being put out. Fan created ISOs are already out there and there's some good stuff. I'd highly recommend this game. If it looks appealing to you, give it a go."
