76561198018474246,Recommended,237870,34595378,Posted: 29 August,all,Goor00,"I've been around. I've played my fair share of survival, crafting, base building and open world games. I went full genocide on fat zombie butts in 7 Days to kick the bucket, I've dived into the abyss of the seven biomes with Subnaughtica, I've clubbed and dismembered naked people in Conan Exiled to play this game, I've used the most versatile vaccum cleaner created by mankind in Astrosmear and played around with other games more or less falling into this category such as The Forest, Savage Lands, Osiris and many, many others.The reason I wrote this long introduction about my knowledge of these games isn't to show off (OK, maybe a little). The point is, I have had hopes for games like these to implement certain concepts and never ever did one of them answer my silent prayers, until I played Planet Explorers.By all means, Planet Explorers is NOT perfect. Actually, there's a bunch of stuff that's bugging me, such as the overall stability of the game which can only be described as... erratic. You can sometimes go on playing for hours without a hitch and all of a sudden, BSOD or something alike. To me, this very clearly puts the game in the ""Early Access"" category. Some quests given by NPC's are buggy (nothing worse than any Bethesda game), there's sometimes odd collision detection and if you want to play the game in all its visual glory, you will need to get hooked up with some guys from the NASA to use their equipment.This being said, what I love the most in this game, is that you can play alone but you're not Robinson Crusoe or Tom Hanks in Castaway. The planet is very much alive with NPC's, enemies, animals and more, making this game one of the most attractive games for one-man wolfpacks such as me who couldn't care less about playing online. You can populate your own settlement with NPC's who have different skills, you actually manage the colony in a quite easy and efficient way (still don't really like some aspects which I think are too tedious). The second homerun comes in the form of the built-in creator. This tool which can be slightly intimidating at first is one of a kind. You can actually build ANYTHING. Cars, boats, robots, planes, trucks, helicopters, armor, weapons, ships... there barely a limit to what you can create. It's amazing and I think just for this, the devs deserve a huge praise.Planet explorers simply feels alive and doesn't leave you as the stranded, lonesome hero who builds huge cities or bases without anyone to live in them, without a proper purpose but your personal satisfaction (yes, I have rebuilt one of the great pyramids in 7 days to die... sue me).To sum it up, if you feel ready to suck it up when the game gives you the finger before crashing to death or mining with a pickaxe in a future that offers plasma guns (go figure), you'll have a blast. It's not a finished game, but it's the closest you'll ever get in shaping a populated world while retaining the best aspects of survival + crafting + building games.Good job, Pathea. You almost have an awesome game there."
