76561198020417994,Recommended,237870,10652219,"Posted: 22 June, 2014",all,ash,"Written as of A0.81 (June 22 2014)My first (~10 hours) hands-on impressions of the game)I didn't read any info about the game before I started it, so I didn't really know what to expect.I started the game, and went into solo-adventurer mode, here I found myself in a camp with some other people (shopkeepers it seemed, some had quests). I bought a shovel, ran out of the camp, and dug a small cave, neat! Then I equipped my dagger (I think it was) and attacked a creature that handed me my genitals on a silver platter. Then I started using some of the materials I dug up when making the cave to make a small hut (creatures are obviously not to be trifled with). About 5min into this I ran out of stamina, and I had no idea how to get it back.So I figured I'd try out the story mode.In story mode I found that there were some questlines to follow, they explained some of the basics, so I no longer want for stamina (or hp).The story mode led me from hub to hub, but I'm still only scratching the surface of this because I was distracted by a looming mountain; ""I wonder if I can dig a tunnel through that mountain"" *2 hours later* ""yeah!"". There is a progression in what schematics you have available, which follows the questline. For example, the first schematics for weapons available are wooden ones, then stone, then iron.The quests I did so far were mainly gather x/kill y/escort z ones, which for me would normally be a big ""thumbs down"", but in this game the backdrop steals the show, and the quests are (imo) mainly there to give you a purpose for why you venture out. I got a quest to gather 20 copper and 5 tin (I think it was) for some guy, and I ended up making a huge underground cave (mining 1000's of copper and tin in the process). I could have finished this quest in 5 minutes, and it would have been a boring gather quest, but because of how the backdrop is made I lost myself in it, and spent literally hours making my very own cave.SummaryMost early access games hold great potential, but Planet explorers, I feel, already has the fundamental basics covered, and this is why I recommend it. It's evident that the people making this know what they are doing, and with the content I've seen so far I don't doubt that they can flesh out the rest.It lacks polish (detailed below), but it has a solid engine. In my first 10 hours of gameplay I haven't had any crashes, and I did stuff like tunnelling through a mountain for fun (this was ~2 hours worth of drilling straight into rock), and then made a big cave where there was a copper deposit.For anyone who can enjoy the simple pleasure it is to shape the world with your mining pick and shovel, there is already a lot of hours worth of gameplay in this game.CaveatI wouldn't recommend it yet to someone who is only/mainly in it for the combat, although this does show promise, it's definitely not balanced - you can build 10 (portable) sentries and wipe out pretty much anything by placing them quickly on the ground near the creature while it's aggressive towards you. It will however cost a lot of bullets having 10 sentry turrets firing away at the same time.Lack of polish examples- not all game modes are quite ready, I recommend you start in story mode, this seems to be the most polished- some of the models lack the detail some other models have (people are very low-poly, but some of the creatures are gorgeous)- there is a help/tutorial system, but it's not very detailed, especially for some of the complex things you can do, like making your own craftable ISOs (blueprints)- a basic tutorial for how to ""live"" is needed (how to regain hp/stamina), there is a quest that explains some of it in story mode, but if you start out in adventurer mode you will be out of luck when you run out of stamina and don't know what to do (sleeping in a bed currently doesn't give stamina, I think it's intended to though)- a few features are not enabled yet- melee combat feels clunkyThe help/tutorial system will likely be lackluster till much later in the developement. It doesn't make much sense to create elaborate explanations of how to do stuff when it is likely to be changed."
76561198033423679,Recommended,237870,10692777,"Posted: 22 June, 2014",all,Big blenny,"This is a great game for survival, creaition and adventure."
,Recommended,237870,10808078,"Posted: 25 June, 2014",all,snugglebuggle,"Awesome and addicting. I was concerned this game wasnt for me when I started playing, but after I got a hang of the controls, I loved the feeling and experience it provided. This really IS an open sandbox adventure/creation game. I totally recommend it."
