,Recommended,237870,11762907,"Posted: 17 August, 2014",all,Evie,"SPOILER: This review is small and pretty opinionated. It isnota comprehensive review on all features and Ihave notexplored every feature availble to the game currently, just most of them. I likely will not explore too much more of the game and it's features but, as I support this game, I will closely monitor it's patches and development.PROS: For the most part, in it's current state, this game is very fun to play.-Multiplayer; being able to gather materials faster and more efficiently to be able to build helicopter gunships for decimating alien encampments is far too much fun. Honestly, after my experience playing the game with my friends, the fun we had was almost criminal.-Hunting; when it comes to hunting these large-scale dinosaur-like creatures, this game really shines. Especially when you have access to better gear so you don't have to rely on hit and run tactics to lure the beasts towards your substantially better equipped AI.-Crafting; holy♥♥♥♥♥♥ Being able to craftrealtechnology is amazing. No more of that unnecessarily complicated, unreasonably restrictive redstone fluffy flutter from Minecraft.Real Technologywith areal impacton gameplay and progression. The list of available recipes is gigantic and, at first, very overwhelming. But it makes the game really something to behold.-Vehicles; worth. Do you like strapping lazer canons and missile silos onto a poorly made car with thrusters and calling it a helicopter gunship? I do. Do you like using that very same vehicle to wreak mayhem and destruction on those god damned Aliens that endlessly spawn from their camps? I do.CONS: That's right, you knew we would get to this part as soon as you saw the word ""pros"". And to a great degree of sadness, this list is much larger than the other one. So much larger, it's hard to pick a good starting place.-Multiplayer; ♥♥♥♥ing port-forwarding. Everyone's least favorite chore. Iliterallyhave friends who would rather pay me their hard-earned, broke college student funds than do their own port-forwarding. Ironically, even I don't like doing it. It's bizarre; it's complicated and simple at the same time. Usually you just go to your router's browser page at 192.168.1.1 and follow some simple directions to get the port forwarded. Combine that with some firewall exceptions and you've got yourself an open port for some multiplayer madness. Assuming it actually works. Which, most of the time, is the problem. There's almostnevera layman's solution to port-forwarding without buying a program to forward the ports for you. You can't just strap in and forward the ports without having to learn the arbitrary process first, it rapidly gets you very involved and educated on how to do it like a professional through a mind-numbing few hours of trial and error. And unless you do it the mythicalright way,which is different per router, you'll find that before long your ports are closed again. tl;dr port forwarding for multiplayer is a bad solution, but a cheap one. Invest a little in better multiplayer and watch the crowds eat up your game.-Hunting; oh boy. Want to hunt something that can'twreckyou like it's name was Ralph? Really boring and offers almost nothing you'll need to build decent survival gear or buy it. Want to hunt something thatactuallygives a worthwhile supply of necessary materials like animal skins and fat or isn't just plain boring to fight? Well be prepared to overly rely on your AI or multiplayer comrades because otherwise it will kill you and♥♥♥♥♥♥your corpse into the ocean. For most of the entire game, it's usually a far safer idea to simply avoid almost everything and mine for materials in vast quantities to be able to emerge from the earth as the most powerful entity on the planet. But then the game is boring because nothing provides a challenge anymore.-Crafting; bore chore. As excellent as the crafting system of this game is at delivering impacful technology that feels as good as it performs... Actually crafting it is obnoxiously boring. It's all about making excessively vast quantities of little materials to be able to make smaller and smaller quantities of larger and larger materials until you have everything you need. The only redeeming feature here is that you can produce things in bulk, which you'll quite often rely on because otherwise you'll have to makeallof the necessary materials over and over again until you no longer need to make whatever oddity you're crafting to begin with. It takes such a long time to make anything worthwhile or important,especiallythe various vehicles in the game.-Vehicles; I didn't sign up for this. The vehicle creation menu/functionality is a very frustrating feature of the game. Especially for those like myself that aren't very creative-minded andSWEATwhen presented that much crafting freedom. As much as I like the freedom offered in the feature, you need to at least present some guidelines or most players will just be lost in the age old question of ""Where the ♥♥♥♥ do I even start?"" Let's not even get that much into the controls of the vehicle crafting feature because all that needs to be said is prepare to rely on the undo function heavily as you constantly mutter ""I didn't want to do that"". Or the arbitrary fact that you have to go into a separate menu just to assign wheels for steering. Last, the fukitol cherry on top, multiplayer additional seating is present in the game but currently not functioning properly or even with any sense of purpose. But I imagine that last bit will be fixed soon.-Gathering; so many problems. Wood gathering? Takes too damn long if you want to get any worthwhile amount of wood that is determined seeminglyat ♥♥♥♥ing randombased on the size of the tree you're chopping down. Mineral gathering? Prepare to scour every inch of the planet trying to evenfindthese materials. They're arbitrarily hard to locate; but I guess that's not so bad when you can mine them in the thousands if you're willing to spend the time doing it once you actually find a vein. Underwater/Oceanic gathering? Unfortunately necessary for the later parts of the game. To make matters worse, to build a boat for easy/safe underwater/oceanic gathering you need oil/petroleum. To get this, you need a boat to be able to safely traverse the waters without getting immediately killed by a dino-shark-demon. I'm sure you see the cycle here.-Voxels/Vertices/Whatever; the last, but greatest con.NEVER IN THIS GAME IS IT WORTH TO MINE WITHOUT AT LEAST A COPPER PICKAXEYou'll mine voxels/vertices/whatever so finely that creating a mine to work in that isn't game breaking or safe to actually stand in is next to impossible unless you're really diligent and have the time on hand to actually do it. Copper pickaxes are one of the first pickaxes that actually mine larger voxels/vertices so you can make flat surfaces for mining much more easily. But again, this is mainly only achievable if you are willing to take the time necessary to actually do that. And based on the reactions of my friends in multiplayer, nobody wantsthatjob.That would be about it. I really enjoy this game, but it just needs a few fixes and gameplay changes. But this should be expected as it is still in alpha. Would I recommend this game? Definitely. Would I recommend this game while it's still in alpha? Yeah, I still would. But there are definitely some fixes that need to happen for the dev team to maximize player enjoyment. If you're sitting on the fence with this game, allow me to say that it's well worth it if you're willing to look past some clear flaws and just have fun playing what works really well. Either way, keep a close eye on the game's development and patches for improvements and fixes; I know I will be."
